text.tspan: Food For Thought College Food Pantry Finder
USER ONE
Jacob, a college sophomore and part-time restaurant worker who would normally get one hot meal a day for free
at work, found himself without his daily main meal or a way to pay for it when the restaurant he worked at
suddenly shuttered. The breakfast bars and ramen he ate between shifts weren't cutting it and he found his mind
wandering during class because of the distraction of hunger.
Jacob had seen the Food for Thought app promoted in various ways on campus and heard of a friend of a friend
who had used it when a scholarship didn't come through as expected. He downloads the app and is quickly
directed to a nearby campus food pantry and a community fridge. It took him just a few minutes to find
resources nearby as he was simply asked to either enable his phone's location finder or enter his zip code. The map
had the address, hours, phone number and website of these locations.
USER TWO
Rachel is an alert and caring assistant professor at a state college. She notices that one of her students who
normally participates in most discussions has recently become listless and a little withdrawn in class. She gently
approaches the student to find that she had an unexpected car repair bill that affected both her ability to get to
work for a week and now the inability to purchase healthy food. Rachel explains the concept of Food for Thought
and shows the student the app and offers to send her the information.
USER THREE
Emily is a college graduate who found a great job 1,000 miles away from her alma mater. She has been working
in her field for a few years and recently heard a podcast about food insecurity on college campuses. While she
never felt real hunger herself during college, the podcast reminded her of people in her circles who were probably
food insecure - and she knew that there were likely more than she realized. She was moved to tears that led to
action. Emily decided to donate to a food pantry near her university via Food for Thought, an app they
mentioned on the podcast. She quickly downloaded the app, clicked on Donate and entered the zip code of her
college campus. She was able access the websites of local food pantries and community fridges from a page that
listed resources in that zip code. She selected one and quickly made a donation that aligned with her values.
